<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Kirkby Thore Parish Council (TIC 080)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from Kirkby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Thore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> Parish Council (TIC 080)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kirkby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a small rural community situated in Eden valley in the east of Cumbria.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The village is situated just off the main A66 trunk road approx 10 miles from Penrith</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and 5 miles from Appleby in Westmorland.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The community is made up of approximately 350 dwellings, 60 of which are designated as social housing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The village has a small shop and post office.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There is little local employment to which people would not hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e to use some form of transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The village is served by the 563 bus service which operates between Kirkby Stephen and Penrith.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The route has 10 services in each direction during the week.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The service generally stops at the bus stop situated on the A6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6 which is at least 1 mile from the vast majority of properties.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There are 4 services (2 in each direction) that call in to the village itself.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kirkby Thore Parish Council successful campaigned to increase the number of services calling into the villa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ge from 2 to 4 in 2012.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Although the Parish Council initially underwrote the cost of these extra services their popularity has deemed them to be self financing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Parish Council believes that the key to rural transport is the improvement of bus servic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es and that to deliver transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improvements a number of issues and authorities will need to work together.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This is something that the Parish Council is actively trying to achieve. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Parish Council is still campaigning for more bus services to call </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in to the village and believes if a number of agencies worked together it would benefit the community as a whole.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If more buses (Cumbria County Council) called into the village less people would need to cross the busy A66, near to a difficult junction wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h poor visibility, to get to the bus shelter (Highways Agency).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If the all the bus services called in to the village and none stopped on the A66 the bus shelter and layby could be used as part of a junction improvement (Highways Agency).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If more bus serv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ices called into the village more people would be able to access employment (Reduction in Benefits).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If more bus services called in to the village the housing association would find it easier to fill properties being vacated as a result of the bedroom tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. (Eden Housing Association).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition the Eden Local Development Plan has identified sites within the Parish where a potential 152 additional properties could be built - a 43% increase in the size of the village.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This Plan however does not detail an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y additional services or improvements that the community could expect if such an increase should occur.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Parish Council hopes that the example and issues described above relating to Kirkby Thore will help demonstrate that the issues rural communitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s face are complex and many; with transport being at the centre of achieving many other benefits, however,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">addressing issues in isolation will not deliver the results rural communities need to survive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>